WEBVTT

00:09.560 --> 00:13.500
Coming up next is the science fiction radio show, so stay with us.

00:29.260 --> 00:34.620
This is the science fiction radio show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.460 --> 00:38.960
And here are your hosts.

00:43.600 --> 00:44.840
This is David Cruz.

00:45.100 --> 00:45.720
And Daryl Lane.

00:46.160 --> 00:50.360
One of the most honored and respected of today's science fiction authors is the English writer

00:50.360 --> 00:51.240
Brian Aldous.

00:51.700 --> 00:56.220
His first science fiction story was published in 1954, and since then he's won every award

00:56.220 --> 00:58.820
the field has to offer, both in this country and throughout Europe.

00:59.260 --> 01:01.200
Aldous is a craftsman of the highest order.

01:01.460 --> 01:06.060
The attention he gives to style, character and structure demonstrates the literary polish

01:06.060 --> 01:08.920
that often distinguishes British science fiction from American.

01:09.320 --> 01:12.920
He's written a few non-science fiction novels in fact that have been bestsellers in England.

01:13.620 --> 01:17.160
We asked him why he chose to concentrate his career in science fiction rather than mainstream

01:17.160 --> 01:17.620
literature.

01:18.640 --> 01:25.020
Well, I regard myself as a writer and this difference that seems to be so apparent to

01:25.020 --> 01:27.440
other people is not so apparent to me.

01:28.800 --> 01:35.700
I'm interested in a kind of literature of ideas and sometimes that strays to one side

01:35.700 --> 01:38.620
of the science fiction fence and sometimes to another.

01:40.260 --> 01:45.760
But it's not as though one day I'm riding a horse and the next day I'm riding a cow.

01:47.280 --> 01:55.700
It's just that I'm in the same vehicle all the time, but sometimes the identification

01:55.700 --> 01:56.760
marks change.

01:57.820 --> 01:59.340
That's the way I see it.

02:00.320 --> 02:05.060
In some of his personal essays on science fiction, Aldous tells of how he was introduced to the

02:05.060 --> 02:08.820
field as a child through Lurid pulp magazines he found at Woolworth's.

02:09.240 --> 02:13.540
His family disapproved of his reading such literature, but Aldous was fascinated and wouldn't

02:13.540 --> 02:14.020
give it up.

02:14.360 --> 02:17.080
He explains why he was so drawn to science fiction at an early age.

02:17.940 --> 02:25.460
I believe it was really that I never had a firm conviction as a child that the world

02:25.460 --> 02:28.480
was as all the grown-ups claimed it to be.

02:29.320 --> 02:36.400
It seemed to me that it was a much more interesting place than any of them believed or that they

02:36.400 --> 02:39.280
sought to deny it was an interesting place at all.

02:39.760 --> 02:45.840
They were all busy working in their shops and making their money and leading their routine

02:45.840 --> 02:46.460
knives.

02:47.800 --> 02:55.260
I was a bit of a scapeologist when I was a child.

02:56.640 --> 03:05.300
I picked up a phrase from an old cowboy movie where one of the wrestlers says out of the

03:05.300 --> 03:09.960
corner of his mouth, let's go while a goreng's good.

03:11.240 --> 03:18.640
And that became a kind of motto for me and at the age of four I was the hottest wrestler

03:18.640 --> 03:23.480
in East Deerham Norfolk and I used to go while the going was good.

03:25.140 --> 03:31.440
So I had that streak of wildness in me I suppose you could say.

03:32.740 --> 03:37.360
Aldous' streak of wildness later led to unique experiments in some of his science fiction

03:37.360 --> 03:37.800
novels.

03:37.800 --> 03:42.240
He gained a reputation as an innovator, as a science fiction author who wasn't afraid

03:42.240 --> 03:45.980
to introduce new styles and concepts into a fairly traditional field.

03:46.520 --> 03:50.840
Two good examples of his innovative techniques were the novels report on probability A in

03:50.840 --> 03:53.320
Barefoot in the Head published in the late 60s.

03:53.860 --> 03:57.360
Their complex styles were avant-garde and confusing to many science fiction readers.

03:57.900 --> 04:01.880
We asked Aldous if he deliberately sought to open up science fiction or enlarge its

04:01.880 --> 04:03.360
boundaries with such experiments.

04:04.540 --> 04:10.260
Would you understand that it's not exactly a motive in writing to expand the field?

04:11.680 --> 04:19.500
I think what you think you're doing at the time is trying to find a little, how should

04:19.500 --> 04:20.420
we mix the metaphor?

04:20.840 --> 04:27.860
Trying to find a little breathing space where the ground isn't too trampled already by the

04:27.860 --> 04:29.180
hordes of other writers.

04:30.580 --> 04:41.360
And so you seek out I suppose the perimeters of the field as it's currently defined.

04:42.440 --> 04:48.920
And in that way if you accidentally extend it well, that's very nice.

04:49.800 --> 04:54.500
And of course some people are grateful to you and other people are very cross with you for

04:54.500 --> 04:56.380
doing it because they say you're breaking the rules.

04:57.200 --> 04:59.720
Next time we'll talk with Brian Aldous about some of his works.

