06:37.640 --> 06:42.100
In 1973 Brian Aldous published a book on the origin and history of science fiction entitled

06:42.100 --> 06:43.180
Billion Years Spree.

06:43.620 --> 06:47.320
He gave us an interesting account of the reasons he wrote the book, including some comments

06:47.320 --> 06:49.420
on one of his novels, Barefoot in the Head.

06:50.240 --> 06:57.060
Well, I'd written a novel called Barefoot in the Head and it really didn't receive

06:58.000 --> 07:02.260
very kind initial attention, although the premise was simple enough.

07:03.580 --> 07:08.700
Barefoot in the Head was about the world stopped in its tracks by drugs.

07:09.040 --> 07:17.240
This was the late 60s, remember, when the Flower Power people had been around and we had had

07:17.240 --> 07:27.660
all this love in stuff and towards the end of the 60s the bills, as we say in England,

07:27.840 --> 07:33.220
the checks were coming in for all that kind of stuff and they were already finding the

07:33.220 --> 07:39.200
foetuses in the trash cans of Heat Ashbury so that Barefoot in the Head was an ambivalent

07:39.200 --> 07:40.980
book written in a difficult language.

07:40.980 --> 07:47.220
But I poured into it all I knew about A. science fiction and B. writing.

07:49.620 --> 07:57.680
And I was a little surprised at the tepid response it got, the angry response it got,

07:57.780 --> 07:58.840
the anonymous letters.

07:59.020 --> 08:02.460
So I thought, well, let's me finish with the science fiction field.

08:03.620 --> 08:10.160
And I thought, well, before I leave it I ought to write down all that I know and love about it

08:11.840 --> 08:12.880
before I forget.

08:13.980 --> 08:19.140
And so really I settled down with that in mind to write Billionaire Spree and also to have

08:19.140 --> 08:24.620
an argument as I raised my hat and left the science fiction or community.

08:26.300 --> 08:31.400
But by the time I got to the end of the thing, you know, three years had passed and

08:33.400 --> 08:36.860
just writing the book turned me on to science fiction again.

08:37.760 --> 08:41.080
Billionaire Spree is full of Aldous's personal but fascinating ideas.

08:41.700 --> 08:46.260
One provocative idea, heresy to some science fiction fans, was that Hugo Gernsback,

08:46.460 --> 08:49.660
the father of modern science fiction, was a disastrous influence on the field.

08:50.020 --> 08:51.760
We asked Aldous what he meant by that.

08:52.360 --> 08:58.460
Well, as you probably know, that I did say something of that sort and since then people

08:58.460 --> 09:03.480
have been threatening to break my legs and my arms and shoot me and hang me and kick

09:03.480 --> 09:06.980
me out of the science fiction field and all sorts of things like that.

09:07.960 --> 09:20.180
But I guess that what I was worried about was the way science fiction was segregated

09:20.180 --> 09:28.180
by Gernsback into a magazine so that if you wanted to find science fiction you had to

09:28.180 --> 09:39.620
go to a magazine that had a name like Astounding or Amazing or Staggering, which had a huge

09:39.620 --> 09:42.620
three-dimensional title with rivets in it.

09:44.440 --> 09:52.780
That resulted in a mono culture and we all know that there are dangers in mono culture.

09:53.780 --> 10:02.100
And I simply thought that the science fiction would be better as an uncaged animal that could

10:02.100 --> 10:04.480
rove at large where it would.

10:05.800 --> 10:13.120
But nowadays people complain that science fiction is segregated and that people think

10:13.340 --> 10:18.920
you're funny if you read it and that it has to have a special place in a bookshop right

10:18.920 --> 10:23.380
next to weirdo cult books about flying saucers or whatever.

10:24.040 --> 10:29.300
Well, my answer to that is that yes, I agree, I think that's too bad.

10:29.660 --> 10:31.980
I think science fiction is much better than that.

10:32.160 --> 10:38.300
But the reason why it is there is because of the segregation that was introduced by Hugo

10:38.300 --> 10:39.080
Gernsback.

10:39.660 --> 10:40.800
That was my argument.

10:41.820 --> 10:45.920
Anyone seeking to gain a perspective on science fiction and fantasy should read Billion

10:45.920 --> 10:50.200
Meier Spree, a personal but fascinating account of the field by one of science fiction's true

10:50.200 --> 10:50.760
men of letters.

10:51.320 --> 10:53.020
Tomorrow more with Brian Aldis.

