12:33.320 --> 12:33.900
And Darrell Ang.

12:34.280 --> 12:38.280
Brian Aldis does unexpected but fascinating things in his science fiction stories.

12:38.720 --> 12:42.820
Though Aldis is often an innovator, he also understands and cherishes the traditions of

12:42.820 --> 12:43.400
science fiction.

12:43.400 --> 12:48.320
Aldis has demonstrated his fondness for science fiction's past by redoing some of its classic

12:48.320 --> 12:48.760
novels.

12:49.160 --> 12:53.720
An island called Moro, for instance, was based on H.G. Wells, the island of Dr. Moro.

12:54.000 --> 12:58.400
In his book, Frankenstein Unbound, drew on Mary Shelley's Frankenstein, published in 1818,

12:58.900 --> 13:00.680
which some call a first science fiction novel.

13:01.280 --> 13:05.040
Aldis relates the impulse behind his writing of Frankenstein Unbound.

13:06.100 --> 13:13.120
I think that I write about the things that fascinate me most, and I'm kind of a literary

13:13.120 --> 13:13.680
man.

13:14.840 --> 13:20.150
And I certainly much admire Mary Shelley's Frankenstein.

13:20.960 --> 13:27.180
It's the most remarkable work for anyone, not least for a young lady, not quite touching

13:27.180 --> 13:27.660
18.

13:28.980 --> 13:38.120
And when I had the impulse to write Frankenstein Unbound, it was really an exegetical impulse

13:38.660 --> 13:45.340
to draw everybody's attention, if possible, to the excellence of that original novel,

13:46.040 --> 13:54.020
which, as you know, has been slandered and pilloried by the filmmakers who've seen nothing

13:54.020 --> 13:59.380
better in it than a stupid, shambling and inarticulate monster.

14:00.260 --> 14:11.340
I wanted to restore the monster to his true evil power as an articulate feeling and maimed

14:11.340 --> 14:17.680
being worthy of our compassion, perhaps our hatred.

14:18.940 --> 14:22.900
Aldis says there was a true creative impulse behind Frankenstein Unbound.

14:22.900 --> 14:25.240
But that wasn't so for an island called Moro.

14:26.280 --> 14:34.220
I have to admit that later on I did the same thing with Wells' Island of Dr. Moro, and

14:35.060 --> 14:38.560
that was, I believe, an advice.

14:39.380 --> 14:49.160
It's one of the few novels I've written that didn't begin with some kind of genuine lust

14:49.160 --> 14:55.440
to create, will to create with fire in my stomach.

14:56.560 --> 15:01.080
I just thought it was something I could do, and that was too tiny a motive, I believe,

15:01.180 --> 15:03.020
for the book that I eventually turned out.

15:03.880 --> 15:11.920
I don't believe that it supersedes or in any way aids the Wells' version.

15:12.720 --> 15:18.100
The funny thing is, I have to say, that that novel was extremely well received.

15:18.100 --> 15:20.800
And in this country and in Great Britain.

15:22.180 --> 15:26.000
Another Aldis tribute to science fiction's past is his novella, The Saliva Tree.

15:26.360 --> 15:31.200
It's a playful book, a clever tribute to H.G. Wells, who happens to be an unseen character in it.

15:31.580 --> 15:35.680
It's about an invisible alien monster ravaging the countryside of late Victorian England.

15:36.200 --> 15:40.660
Invading monsters and invisibility are two of Wells' themes, of course, and during the story,

15:40.820 --> 15:44.140
all of Wells' themes and the titles of his books are somehow worked in.

15:44.140 --> 15:48.420
The story's main character, Gregory Rolls, has been writing letters to H.G. Wells

15:48.420 --> 15:49.940
about the happenings in the countryside.

15:50.640 --> 15:52.760
Wells comes to meet Rolls as the story ends.

15:53.840 --> 16:03.760
Our central character is about to relate to H.G. Wells the horrific events that have gone on down on the farm.

16:05.160 --> 16:14.460
And in those events are really the germs for all of Wells' science fiction.

16:16.020 --> 16:22.440
I mean, you know, there's a kind of a joke on H.G. Wells there.

16:22.720 --> 16:30.300
I mean, we all owe a great debt to H.G. Wells because he preempted almost all of the science fiction themes.

16:31.020 --> 16:37.080
And so in a way, the saliva tree is a kind of horrific joke to show that in fact,

16:37.480 --> 16:39.480
Wells didn't have any original ideas.

16:39.700 --> 16:44.400
They were all given to him by this guy who knocks on the door at the end of the story.

16:45.660 --> 16:47.920
More on the works of Brian Aldis next time.

