18:30.300 --> 18:34.540
English science fiction author Brian Aldis sometimes writes books which are difficult to categorize.

18:34.800 --> 18:41.440
Aldis has written familiar science fiction such as his first novel, which was published in this country in 1959 as Starship.

18:41.840 --> 18:45.320
But many of his novels are experimental or avant-garde in both theme and structure.

18:45.320 --> 18:49.580
Report on Probability A published in 1969 is a good example of his type.

18:50.160 --> 18:57.120
A 1976 novel though, The Melasia Tapestry, is one of his most unique novels, a strange but richly rewarding book.

18:57.500 --> 18:59.000
And it completely resists categories.

18:59.520 --> 19:01.900
It could be called science fiction, but it's not quite that.

19:02.420 --> 19:04.500
Some might say it's fantasy, but it's not that either.

19:04.960 --> 19:07.420
Aldis talks about the inspiration behind the book.

19:08.380 --> 19:14.080
The model I had was a pictorial one.

19:14.360 --> 19:15.180
That's often the case.

19:17.160 --> 19:23.960
Well, in several of my novels, I start from a pictorial beginning.

19:24.960 --> 19:38.720
And my pictorial beginnings with Melasia were the etchings which the Italian artist, the Baroque artist, G.B.T. Epileau, made at the end of his life.

19:39.700 --> 19:53.060
Towards the end of his life, he retired and he started etching these mysterious little pictures of women.

19:54.260 --> 20:10.380
Wizards, Monte Banks, soldiers, punchinellos, people being dug out of the ground from graves, owls, serpents burning on altars.

20:10.760 --> 20:14.200
All sorts of mysterious symbols in these lovely little pictures.

20:15.020 --> 20:17.240
And no one's actually figured out what they meant to be.

20:17.240 --> 20:30.480
It's like a science-fiction alternative world where magic rules, I suppose you'd say, and I suppose that was one of the things I liked about them.

20:31.560 --> 20:40.000
So I thought, well, if no one else can reconstruct this world to their satisfaction, I'll have a go at it.

20:41.200 --> 20:49.980
And so I started writing short stories around the more haunting of these etchings of T. Epileaus.

20:50.920 --> 20:56.940
Melasia itself is a grand city which exists in what appears to be an alternate universe, suggestive of Earth's ancient past.

20:57.440 --> 21:05.300
There is no technology to speak of, sorcery of a limited sort seems to work, and there are all manner of exotic creatures such as flying beings which resemble humans.

21:05.300 --> 21:12.400
The novel's main concern is art, an unusual theme for a science-fiction or fantasy book, seemingly more appropriate for a romantic poet.

21:12.840 --> 21:17.100
Aldous told us that the theme of art came out of a serious illness he had while writing the book.

21:18.020 --> 21:39.320
The effect of this internal complaint I had, this hepatitis, made me feel that, well, my lifespan was limited, and I'd froliced about a good deal and had written some books that I perhaps didn't take as seriously as I should do,

21:40.620 --> 21:47.280
and that what I dearly loved was writing, and that I wanted to make a statement about art.

21:49.660 --> 21:54.460
And really, Melasia is, it's all about art from the title onwards.

21:54.460 --> 22:12.400
In other words, if the book has a power, it is the power of meditations on the nature of art, which is at once to transfigure, and at the same time to petrify.

22:12.400 --> 22:22.340
And as you know, Melasia itself is a city-state under a curse of zero change.

22:23.740 --> 22:34.180
Well, that's like a work of art, it's like Tiepolo's little etchings. They may be forever enigmatic to us, but they're forever unchanging.

22:35.060 --> 22:42.100
The Melasia Tapestry by one of the masters of modern science fiction, a difficult novel to categorize but a fascinating one to read.

