24:26.380 --> 24:32.560
Brian Aldous' latest science fiction novel is the masterful achievement of an author who is at the height of his very awesome powers.

24:32.560 --> 24:38.200
It's called Heliconia Spring, and it's the first volume of a trilogy about an Earth-like planet called Heliconia.

24:38.540 --> 24:40.860
Aldous tells us about the planet and the books.

24:42.760 --> 24:50.600
Heliconia is the name of a planet that's really much like Earth, and a lot of Earth-like things go on there.

24:51.540 --> 25:04.340
But it is the child of binary suns, and it takes two and a half thousand years to go around the primary.

25:05.320 --> 25:08.780
I mean two and a half thousand Earth years.

25:11.560 --> 25:23.700
Which is to say that between one winter and the next, you can have a whole lot of civilizations doing a whole lot of declining and falling.

25:25.160 --> 25:27.880
And of course, falling and rising.

25:28.880 --> 25:38.940
And so that these three long volumes really just cover parts of one of Heliconia's great years.

25:40.000 --> 25:52.220
So there's at once this marvellous continuity, as I see it, of one year and yet of many generations and many cultures.

25:53.820 --> 25:56.640
And that's the basic plan of the book.

25:57.060 --> 26:01.420
They're simply titled, The First One's Heliconia Spring, that's the one that's out.

26:01.860 --> 26:08.500
The one I'm writing is Heliconia Summer, and after that I go on to Heliconia Winter.

26:22.220 --> 26:26.700
The first volume traces the life of a nomadic hunter named Yuli and his descendants.

26:27.620 --> 26:30.800
Because the first volume is about the sun bursting out.

26:32.560 --> 26:40.200
The first volume is just stacked full of things bursting out, and people bursting out, animals bursting out.

26:41.460 --> 26:43.560
It's a great bursting out novel.

26:51.440 --> 26:58.700
Circling Heliconia is a satellite from Earth, a huge observation station which monitors everything that happens in Heliconia and beams it to Earth.

26:59.120 --> 27:03.820
Aldous spent a painstaking four years on the book, striving for accuracy and realism.

27:05.040 --> 27:09.780
Well, I hope people will find that it's full of reality.

27:10.640 --> 27:19.920
That's why I say the moral of it should be mere existence, because I think they recognize their own lives passing through the book.

27:21.000 --> 27:35.960
And the other motive I had was that I grew rather alarmed at the way so much science fiction, since it's become more popular,

27:37.020 --> 27:43.060
has been full of, what shall we say, fantasy, wish fulfillment.

27:44.020 --> 27:55.960
I didn't like that. I think that science fiction should reflect the facts of life, the hard facts of life.

27:56.760 --> 28:08.080
It shouldn't just be some nonsense about one guy against a malign empire who goes out and kills the chief baddie.

28:08.760 --> 28:16.420
I thought it should have a little more contact for reality, and moreover, I'll sound old fashioned if I say this,

28:16.920 --> 28:27.640
but I think that sort of thing is better for the nation's youth than the old hogwash about telepathic dragons and all the rest of it.

28:34.540 --> 28:41.780
Hello, Coney, a spring is a remarkable and unique achievement by a man who is not just a great science fiction writer, but one of the finest writers of our time.

